<subSubSection pageId="142" pageNumber="143" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="142.[189,342,1427,1453]" box="[189,342,1427,1453]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,1427,1453]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1427,1453]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="142.[189,1399,1474,1606]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
AL, AT, BA, BE, BG, BY, 
<collectingCountry box="[516,560,1474,1500]" name="Switzerland" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">CH</collectingCountry>
, CZ, DE, DK-DEN, ES-SPA, FI, FR-FRA, GB-CI, GB-GRB, GB-NI, HR, HU, IE, IT-ITA, LT, LU, LV, MC, MK, NL, NO-NOR, PL, RO, RU-KGD, RU-RUC, RU-RUE, RU-RUN, SB, SE, SI, SK, UA. Most of Europe, from the Mediterranean to the Boreal Zones and east to the Ural Mts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="142" pageNumber="143" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="142.[189,285,1644,1670]" box="[189,285,1644,1670]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,285,1644,1670]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,285,1644,1670]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Habitat</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="142.[189,1399,1691,1999]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">
Eurytopic, with an altitudinal range of nearly 
<quantity box="[741,834,1691,1718]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" unit="m" value="3000.0">3000 m</quantity>
, though it is particularly associated with warm habitats and sandy areas. It is often abundant in sand dune systems and is closely associated with heaths but may be found on limestone as well as sandstone. It is common in more or less open woods on lighter soils but, in 
<collectingCountry box="[333,434,1797,1823]" name="Belgium" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Belgium</collectingCountry>
at least, it is almost never observed in large closed forests. Yet, in Eastern Europe it is dominant in some 
<taxonomicName box="[463,561,1832,1858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[463,561,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[621,688,1833,1858]" class="Spermatopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Picea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Coniferales" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[621,688,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="142" pageNumber="143">Picea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stands in the Byelovezskaya Puzcha (
<bibRefCitation author="Tarasevich Y. L." box="[1142,1339,1832,1858]" pageId="142" pageNumber="143" pagination="213 - 218" refId="ref62383" refString="Tarasevich Y. L. 1992. Diplopoda in the associations of mixed forests in Byelorussia. Berichte des naturhistorisch-medizinischen Vereins Innsbruck, Supplementum 10: 213 - 218." type="journal article" year="1992">Tarasevich 1992</bibRefCitation>
) and it occurs in the taiga. Adults wander into a very wide variety of habitats from lowland woodlands and grasslands to alpine meadows, usually during the summer. In winter it appears to be more restricted to damper places occurring in the leaf litter and superficial layers of well drained soil. There are several references to its occurrence in wetlands and on moors, including peat bogs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="143.[189,303,267,293]" box="[189,303,267,293]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,267,293]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="143.[189,1399,313,692]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
One of the most widely dispersed millipedes in Europe, from 
<geoCoordinate box="[931,1002,314,340]" degrees="38" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" precision="55555" value="38.0">38° N</geoCoordinate>
in Calabria to 
<geoCoordinate box="[1184,1255,313,340]" degrees="64" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" precision="55555" value="64.0">64° N</geoCoordinate>
in the taiga of 
<collectingCountry box="[224,318,348,374]" name="Finland" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Finland</collectingCountry>
. It has not yet been recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[753,839,349,375]" name="Greece" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Greece</collectingCountry>
, some major Mediterranean islands and much of 
<collectingCountry box="[225,296,384,410]" name="Georgia" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Iberia</collectingCountry>
, where many other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latzel" authorityYear="1884" box="[676,834,384,410]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Ommatoiulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[676,834,384,410]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Ommatoiulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur. Records from 
<collectingCountry box="[1103,1202,384,410]" name="Portugal" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Portugal</collectingCountry>
are not reliable (N. Akkari, pers. comm.) It is active in summer when many other species are dormant, spatially very patchy and it undergoes large population fluctuations. Mass swarming has been observed on many occasions (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Ehrnsberger R." box="[384,600,489,516]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" pagination="199 - 203" refId="ref56158" refString="Ehrnsberger R. 2002. Massenauftreten und Wanderung des Diplopoden Ommatoiulus sabulosus in Westniedersachsen. Osnabrucker Naturwissenschaftliche Mitteilungen 28: 199 - 203." type="journal article" year="2002">Ehrnsberger 2002</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Helb H. W." box="[616,746,489,516]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" pagination="376 - 381" refId="ref57993" refString="Helb H. W. 1975. Zum Massenauftreten von Schizophyllum sabulosum im Saarland. Entomologica Germanica 1: 376 - 381." type="journal article" year="1975">Helb 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kania G. &amp; Tracz H." box="[762,1015,489,516]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" pagination="57 - 66" refId="ref58595" refString="Kania G. &amp; Tracz H. 2005. Mass occurrence and migration of Ommatoiulus sabulosus (Linnaeus, 1758) (Diplopoda: Julida: Julidae) in Poland. Peckiana 4: 57 - 66." type="journal article" year="2005">Kania &amp; Tracz 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Voigtlander K." box="[1030,1241,489,516]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" pagination="181 - 187" refId="ref63284" refString="Voigtlander K. 2005. Mass occurrences and swarming behaviour of millipedes (Diplopoda: Julidae) in Eastern Germany. Peckiana 5: 181 - 187." type="journal article" year="2005">Voigtländer 2005</bibRefCitation>
). An entirely black form without the two characteristic orange dorsal stripes, 
<emphasis box="[984,1024,525,551]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">O.s.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Risso, 1826)" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1826" box="[1023,1362,524,551]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Iulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aimatopodus">
<emphasis box="[1023,1183,525,551]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">aimatopodus</emphasis>
(Risso, 1826)
</taxonomicName>
, is known from some southern departments of 
<collectingCountry box="[693,777,560,586]" name="France" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">France</collectingCountry>
. We treat 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Attems" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[888,1048,560,586]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Ommatoiulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irregularis">
<emphasis box="[888,1048,560,586]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">O. irregularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1248,1399,560,586]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Palaioiulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sabulosus">
<emphasis box="[1248,1399,560,586]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">O. sabulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the advice of Nesrine Akkari, who has seen Attems’ 
<typeStatus box="[853,904,596,622]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">type</typeStatus>
specimen. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Attems" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[1039,1203,595,621]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Ommatoiulus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="irregularis">
<emphasis box="[1039,1203,595,621]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">O. irregularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was included in the Italian checklist (
<bibRefCitation author="Strasser C. &amp; Minelli A." box="[435,723,630,656]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" pagination="193 - 212" refId="ref61938" refString="Strasser C. &amp; Minelli A. 1984. Elenco dei diplopodi d'Italia. Lavori Societa veneziana Scienze naturali 9: 193 - 212." type="journal article" year="1984">Strasser &amp; Minelli 1984</bibRefCitation>
) with a question mark, but excluded from the later list of 
<bibRefCitation author="Foddai D. &amp; Minelli A. &amp; Scheller U. &amp; Zapparoli M." box="[189,426,665,692]" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" pagination="32" refId="ref57437" refString="Foddai D., Minelli A., Scheller U. &amp; Zapparoli M. 1995. Chilopoda, Diplopoda, Pauropoda, Symphyla. In: Minelli A., Ruffo S. &amp; La Posta S. (eds) Checklist delle Specie della Fauna italiana 32. Calderini, Bologna." type="book chapter" year="1995">
Foddai 
<emphasis box="[278,337,665,691]" italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">et al.</emphasis>
(1995)
</bibRefCitation>
. Numerous other forms have been named but are not listed here.
</paragraph>
